Comment: This is going to get me flamed, but this is the latest data point supporting the argument that money does not win elections. I mean, you still have to hire staff, put out ads, and get your candidate and their message in front of voters. But the kind of zany crap that Musk is pulling, and the outrageous billions other donors are pumping into campaigns don't seem to be working.  money can buy you politicians, but it can't buy voters.  edit: let me put it another way. its like auto racing. If you have a good team and a good car, you will do better than the racer who has neither. But if you have all that, and a genius driver, you will always win. money can get you the car and the team, but it doesn't always get you the driver. a poor team can have a great driver and still beat a rich team with a bad driver.   Musk dumped his money on a losing team. What's more, everybody SAW him dumping his money on that team, which likely turned out the support for the liberal judge. Comment: it kind of worked. Money can buy you a strong campaign structure, which can make the difference in an election. By that, I mean it can pay for door-knockers, phone banks, voter data, and expensive analysts and consultants. That also means it can buy you cheats, assuming that is what Musk was able to do. But that isn't guaranteed to overcome voter [sentiment.You](http://sentiment.You) can get all the celebrity endorsements, guest-spots on talk shows, and advertising you want. if the voters hate you, you should probably just curl up and die.    People around the world voted to oust incumbent governments. Its like this, whoever was in power during the Covid-19 pandemic got booted whenever the next election came along. After the pandemic came a global wave of inflation, and whoever was in power during *that* period *also* got booted in the next election. People were going to kick Trump, one way or the other. But Biden was similarly doomed. No amount of money was going to save either of those guys. Without some drastic actions (actions that safe and sane Biden would never take) the Democrats were destined to lose the White House.  I should probably dig up some statistics to back my argument up, but this is an assertion I have often read from political analysts. It's not a popular argument to make because the general effect of dumping money into any other contest is that the richer guy wins. And it also doesn't account for the less direct ways that money corrupts: buying the support of elected politicians, for instance. Money in politics is bad for people without money. Money in *elections* doesn't seem to be a big deal.
